##Iran's Vice Minister of health is confirmed, death rate is extremely high and prevention and control experience is lacking

Wechat, chinanewsweekly

Function introduction, here is "China News weekly" the head of the weekly gentleman, the influence has the influence you. Come with me to break through the fog, to find the truth, to watch the Times.

"Iran is very good at dealing with earthquakes,

But they have no experience in infectious disease control."

SCREENSHOT: Harry (left) wipes his face during a press conference.

Iran's deputy health minister and spokesman, Iraj Harirchi, tested positive for the new coronavirus on Feb. 25. Later, Harry himself posted a Selfie in which he admitted he was infected with the virus, joking that "the virus is democratic and does not recognize poverty or riches and honor" .

A day earlier, the Associated Press quoted Iran's semi official news agency as saying that 50 people had died of pneumonia caused by the new coronavirus infection in the Shiite holy city of Qom this month. Since Feb. 13,50 people have died from new pneumonia in Qom, and more than 250 are under quarantine, according to city official Ahmad Amiriabadi Farahani. But it was only on February 19 that the Iranian government officially reported the cases for the first time.

Harry, however, denies this. Al Arabiya reported that he also said "I will resign" if the number of deaths from the new coronavirus in Qom is a quarter of what is reported in the media. But he acknowledged that about 900 suspected cases are currently being tested.

Khaleesi is one of Iran's main epidemic prevention work, often in the first line of work, and with suspected patients have had close contact. Recently, he has attended many press conferences, given television interviews, did not wear a mask and other protective measures, and fever, sneezing and other symptoms appear. At a news conference broadcast on Iranian state television, Harry was sweating and wiping. The next day, he was diagnosed.

After Harry's confirmation, a member of Iran's parliament, Mahmoud Sadji, also posted on social media that he had new pneumonia.

According to figures released by the Iranian Ministry of Health on February 25th, 16 people have died of COVID-19 pneumonia in Iran, bringing the total to 95.

World Health Organization (WHO) director-general Tan Desai said at a media briefing on 24, although the new crown epidemic has not yet reached the global pandemic level, but countries should be ready for a potential pandemic.

The death rate is well above the world average

According to official Iranian data, the death rate in Iran is higher than in any other country, accounting for nearly 17 percent of the total number of infected people, well above the world average. The current death rate from COVID-19 infection is about 2 percent, according to a World Health Organization report last week.

As early as Feb. 13, there were reports of suspected new coronavirus infections in Iran, but Iranian officials later denied that the cases were related to the new coronavirus because the infected people had not been to China.

On February 11th, millions of people poured into the streets of Iran as usual for the Victory Day of the Islamic Revolution.

The first confirmed case of a new crown disease in Iran was reported on 19 February, the day on which both patients died. The confirmed cases, both from the holy city of Qom in Iran, had no contact with the Chinese, had never been outside the country, and even Qom had never left.

Subsequently, the number of confirmed cases in Iran increased rapidly, 13 cases were added on the 21st, including 2 deaths, 10 cases on the 22nd, including 1 death... on the 25th, a sudden increase of 34 cases and 4 deaths. But so far, the source of the infection has not been identified.

Minou Mohrez, an Iranian health ministry official, said the virus had reached many cities, including Tehran, Babol, Arak, Isfahan and Rasht, "It is clear that the COVID-19 has begun to spread in Iran, " said Rakhmanzade, the mayor of Tehran's 13th district, who was also quarantined, according to the Associated Press.

Schools across much of the country have been suspended and football games and movies have been suspended to prevent the spread of the virus. The capital, Tehran, has been disinfected daily on subways and buses.

Parsa, a Tehran resident, told China News weekly that life is still normal and there are not many people wearing masks on the streets of Tehran because people are told that only infected people and contacts of infected people need to wear masks when they go out. "But there are also people who are hoarding supplies they can't use up, including food and so on, which is causing a lot of shortages. "

Iran's epidemic is spreading to the international community. In Canada, Lebanon and the United Arab Emirates, there have been imported cases from Iran. On 24 February alone, five Middle Eastern countries announced the first new cases in their territories -- in Afghanistan, Bahrain, Iraq, Kuwait and Oman -- all linked to Iran. Three of the cases announced by Kuwait were among 700 people evacuated from the North Eastern city of Mashhad last week, but Iran has not reported any cases of Mashhad. This, coupled with the contrast between media reports and official figures, has raised questions about the Iranian government's message.

Michael E. Ryan, the WHO's executive director for emergency programmes, said the Iranian epidemic was still in its early stages of development and that the Iranian government was likely to have only noticed cases with very severe symptoms.

Five neighbors -- Pakistan, Iraq, Turkey, Afghanistan and Armenia -- have already announced the closure of their borders with Iran. In addition, a number of countries have suspended traffic with Iran.

On Feb. 23, Iranian President Rohani told a cabinet meeting that Tehran would use military force to contain the outbreak and minimize the damage. According to Press TV, Rohani also issued an order on the same day, requesting Iran's Health Minister, Namaki, to take the lead in setting up a national epidemic prevention and Control Headquarters.

Iran has no intention of sealing off the worst affected region, despite public information that most of the cases have come from Qom. Mayor Qom said on the evening of February 25th that blockading the city was "not an appropriate solution" .

Musan, an official with the Ministry of Commerce of Iran, told China Newsweek that this is a very serious matter now, "but you should know that the epidemic has been played up very badly by the Western media. "

Lack of prevention and control experience, limited medical resources

Located about 150 kilometers south of Tehran, Qom is an important Shiite pilgrimage site, with a population of more than 1 million, receiving about 22.5 million tourists each year.

Xu Song, an employee of a Chinese owned institution who had visited Qom several times on business trips, told China news weekly that Qom's economic level was average because it was a religious holy city, but people came and went very frequently, every year, one million or even ten million pilgrims travel to Qom. And it's not just the Iranians; Muslims in other countries, as long as they are Shia, regard Qom as a holy city.

In the early 9th century, the Ali Al-Ridha built the tomb of his sister, Fatimah Zahra Masouma, in Qom. It is also home to Qom Hawza, the largest Shia seminary, where Ruhollah Khomeini, Iran's revolutionary leader, lectured as a young man.

There were no tall buildings in Qom, the streets were narrow, there were many mosques, pilgrims were everywhere, there were crowds, women were wrapped from head to toe in black robes, Xu Song said. The sanitation of the streets and the medical, health, and sanitation capabilities of Qom are far inferior to those of large cities such as Tehran and Isfahan. "I've never been to the local hospital in Qom, but it's very small on the outside. "

According to the Financial Times, Iran's ability to respond to the outbreak has been a source of concern because of years of US sanctions. If the number of infected people is too large, Iran is unlikely to have sufficient equipment and resources to screen, diagnose and treat patients.

In the ILNA report, Farahani said none of the local nurses had proper protective gear, that some medical experts had left Qom, and that the government had taken no special action against Qom, "The government has not been very successful in controlling the virus, " he said.

Hua Liming, a former Chinese ambassador to Iran, said the problem probably lies in Iran's lack of experience in preventing and controlling large-scale epidemics, and the lack of effective means and measures for prevention and control.

In terms of climate, the whole of Iran is dry and dry with a lot of light, Hua told China News Weekly. In terms of diet, the Muslim diet is relatively narrow and fastidious. Meat is basically beef and mutton, chicken, fish only eat scaleless, and there are strict rules for the slaughter of animals, such as inserting a knife a few inches from the animal's neck, animal blood has to be drained, et CETERA, et CETERA. If an animal is killed by a fall or a gun, they don't eat it. So, in terms of natural conditions and the way of life, Iran is one of those countries that are less vulnerable to the plague. In history, there has not been a large-scale epidemic, in recent years in Atypical pneumonia, H1N1 and other outbreaks of epidemic impact on Iran is not very large, there is no large-scale outbreak in Iran.

"The main disaster facing Iran is the earthquake. They are very good at dealing with the earthquake, but they have no experience in the prevention and control of infectious diseases, " Hua said.

According to statistics published by the World Health Organization, in 2003, there were a total of 8,422 cases of SARS in the world, involving 32 countries and regions, with zero cases in Iran that year. From 2012 to 30 June 2019, a total of 2,449 cases of Middle East Respiratory Syndrome coronavirus (Mers) infection were reported to who globally, including 845 deaths in 27 countries, mainly in the Middle East, North Africa and South Korea, iran has reported six cases of infection.

Iran ranks 69th in the Bloomberg L.P.'s 2019 National Health Index, which measures environmental, medical and health risks across countries. Iran has one of the best health system in the region, says Aboubakar Oumarou, a member of the WHO's regional office for the eastern Mediterranean.

According to Xu Song, the medical level in the Iranian capital Tehran is relatively high, and the hardware and software level of large public hospitals is comparable to that of the domestic Grade III, Class A hospital. However, there are only a few large hospitals of this level in the whole of Tehran, there are plenty of small clinics run by specialists themselves. Once the outbreak of large-scale infectious diseases, these small clinics are afraid to be able to receive diagnosis, confirmed infection.

Iran's health minister said Feb. 23, every city in Iran will set up at least a new designated pneumonia hospital, in Tehran and other major cities may increase, treatment free of charge. At least 230 hospitals across the country will receive new patients with pneumonia.

Xu Song was given a pseudonym to protect the privacy of the interviewees
